The average y/y growth rate for China is expected by economists to be 6.1% for Q2 2021 (this is the statistic that the question refers to not annualized growth). Though the Chinese economy did amazing well y/y in Q1 2021 (118.1) this was due to the large drop in Q1 2020. Even if growth were the same from Q1 to Q2 then the growth would still not be nearly as robust in y/y terms because the growth references the previous quarter in the previous year not the annualized growth for the year or the growth between quarters. Still seems most likely to be ~6.5%.

Q4 2020 numbers came out as 6.5% increase year over year. Based on that I'm increasing confidence in Q2 being over 8%. Comparing nominal GDP numbers to the index China has reported I'm estimating that inflation is low, which makes sense when coming out of a recession, so that shouldn't be subtracting from the nominal growth numbers too much. In a normal year Q2 is generally about 4.5% to 6.3% below the GDP of the previous Q4. Even if Q2 2021 is 6.3% below Q4 2020 the GDP for Q2 2021 would be 27.76 trillion yuan, which would be about 11% over the GDP for Q2 2020 of 25.01 trillion yuan. That's before inflation, so inflation would deduct a bit from that, but with fairly low inflation coming out of the recession it's hard to see inflation exceeding 3%.

Now that the question is focused around rate (and not growth target) the probabilities shift greatly. The Chinese economy seems to have been doing fairly well especially with respect to other economies because more stringent (draconian) Chinese measures at halting the spread of COVID seem to have worked in some part. Nevertheless, the Chinese economy has two major issues waying it down which will keep the growth rate from being above 7.0% in my view. First, the large amount of privately held debt (as much as %188 of GDP per the IMF: https://www.imf.org/external/datamapper/PVD_LS@GDD/CHN). Second, the semi-export focus of the current Chinese economy and the desire by the regime to increase the ratio of domestic to foreign consumption of Chinese products (https://www.voanews.com/east-asia-pacific/voa-news-china/china-plans-lift-economy-boosting-consumption#:~:text=Consumption%20growth,manufacturing%2Doriented%20economy%20remain%20stable.) As domestic consumption can only grow slowly compared to growing export focus (growing domestic consumption requires growing internal wealth which takes time vs. selling exports to gain wealth from other countries' consumers which already have it). Thus, Chinese growth will be relatively strong, but not spectular compared to previous years (i.e., above 6% but below 8%).
